[1
Date: Thu, 16 Nov 2000 12:48:08 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: TOMRIC Agency, Fri 10 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200011100280.html>

Suspected Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever Case in Northern Tanzania
------------------------------------------------------------
DAR ES SALAAM: A suspected case of Ebola hemorrhagic fever [is under
observation at Kanyigo ward in Bukoba Rural district in the Kagera
Region. The Ministry of Health has said that [clinical samples will be
sent to South Africa or Zambia for analysis.
Reports from Kagera Regional Medical Officer's office said that the victim,
who was admitted at Kanyigo Health centre, traveled regularly between
Tanzania and Uganda. Recently, fear of an outbreak of Ebola fever has
increased in northern Tanzania, especially in Kagera, Mwanza, Arusha, Tanga
and Kilimanjaro regions.
******
[2
Date: Thu, 16 Nov 2000 12:49:52 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: African Eye News Service (South Africa), Tue 7 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200011070416.html>

Suspected Case of Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever Reported in Tanzania
--------------------------------------------------------------
DAR ES SALAAM: Tanzanian health authorities on Tue 7 Nov 2000 launched a
probe into the country's first suspected case of Ebola hemorrhagic fever in
the western border region of Kagera. National Health Permanent Secretary
Mariam Mwaffisi confirmed that the government had dispatched a team of
experts to Kagera, on Tanzania's border with Uganda, after unconfirmed
reports that an Ebola fever patient had been admitted to Kanyigo Clinic. The
clinic, in the heavily populated Muleba Rural District, serves the same
region where HIV/AIDS was first reported in 1983. "We dispatched the
task-team the moment we received initial reports, but want to caution people
that last time we had a reported Ebola fever case it turned out to be
nothing more than a serious malaria infection," said Mwaffisi.
She declined to comment further until the task-team tabled its report.
Initial unconfirmed reports on a possible Ebola case first surfaced on
Sunday, with Kagera's Regional Medical Office confirming one suspected
Ebola case at Kanyigo Clinic on Monday. Tanzania began taking precautionary
measures to contain and treat Ebola fever immediately after the outbreak
was reported in neighboring Uganda's southwestern regions last month. The
outbreak appears to be spreading south, with 91 reported dead and 190
infected to date. A further 16 people are under surveillance for possible
Ebola infection at Mbarara University Hospital, after reportedly coming
into contact with a Ugandan army Private who died of Ebola fever at the
hospital on 27 Oct 2000.
[Byline: John Ongeri
